<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-02-08T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-02-08T14:00:00-05:00" n="238" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d238">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">835.5151/623: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Weddell</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-02-08T14:00:00-05:00">February 8, 1937—2
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>20. Your 16, February 4, midnight. Please report by cable what specific
                            provisions in the Anglo-Argentine agreement you have in mind in your
                            statement that “Argentina might be more lenient if there were some
                            assurance that the British Government would not insist upon a too strict
                            interpretation of the Anglo-Argentine trade agreement”.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>